aes Y Groes, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1104–1192":"1104–1192","1102–Male":"1102–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1112–Female":"1112–Overleden","1075–1150":"1075–1150","1051–1111":"1051–1111","1070–1132":"1070–1132","1106":"1106","1104":"1104","1102":"1102","1112":"1112","1111":"1111","1132":"1132","1075":"1075","1150":"1150","1051":"1051","1192":"1192","1070":"1070","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales":"Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Maes Gwenllian, Wales":"Maes Y Groes, Flintshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1104–1192":"1104–1192","1102–Male":"1102–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1112–Female":"1112–Deceased","1075–1150":"1075–1150","1051–1111":"1051–1111","1070–1132":"1070–1132","1106":"1106","1104":"1104","1102":"1102","1112":"1112","1111":"1111","1132":"1132","1075":"1075","1150":"1150","1051":"1051","1192":"1192","1070":"1070","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales":"Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Maes Gwenllian, Wales":"Maes Y Groes, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Abt  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name from Apt, the Yiddish name of Opatów in Świętokrzyskie Voivodeship, Poland. The placename (in German, Yiddish, and Polish) is from a root meaning ‘abbot’, the place having been named for the local abbey. Compare   Abt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Cadwgan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Cadogan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"Gruffydd","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: The Welsh name; from creffydd, strong faith, or strong in faith. Gruffydd, a Welsh form of Gryffydd."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":2,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Gruffydd ap Cadwgan was born in 1104, in Nannau, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Cadwgan ap Bleddyn, was 53 and his mother, Unnamed Daughter Picot de Say, was 34. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with